Is there a reason these need to be `haveI` rather than `have`?
The only reason is that I haven't fully converted from Lean3 syntax. Should I also change this elsewhere in the file, or will that make the diff too weird?

```suggestion
theorem isFraisseLimit_of_countable_infinite
    (M : Type*) [Countable M] [Infinite M] [Language.empty.Structure M] :
    IsFraisseLimit { S : Bundled Language.empty.Structure | Finite S } M where
  age := by
    ext S
    simp only [age, Structure.fg_iff_finite, mem_setOf_eq, and_iff_left_iff_imp]
    intro hS
    simp
  ultrahomogeneous S hS f := by
    classical
    have : Finite S := hS.finite
    have : Infinite { x // x âˆ‰ S } := ((Set.toFinite _).infinite_compl).to_subtype
    have : Finite f.toHom.range := (((Substructure.fg_iff_structure_fg S).1 hS).range _).finite
    have : Infinite { x // x âˆ‰ f.toHom.range } := ((Set.toFinite _).infinite_compl ).to_subtype
    refine âŸ¨StrongHomClass.toEquiv (f.equivRange.subtypeCongr nonempty_equiv_of_countable.some), ?_âŸ©
    ext x
    simp [Equiv.subtypeCongr]
```
if you'd like, you can golf this quite a bit! 

The last `simp` does require 
`@[simps toEquiv_apply]
noncomputable def equivRange`
in Substructures.lean though. I think the `simps` setup for some of these structures doesn't look quite optimal, but the general fixes can be a later PR.

Thanks for the golf - I did try doing something with `classical`, but I don't know why it didn't work.

Could you point out to me what kind of changes you'd suggest to the `simps` setup?
(Probably a conversation for Zulip, because I agree it's better to save them for a later PR)
